<seg id=1> Ding Hao Grew Up In Chinese Orphanage, Now First Handicapped University Student </seg>
</hl>
<p>
<seg id=2> XINHUA NEWS AGENCY WIRE Hangzhou, Sept. 1 (Zhu Guoxian reporting with intern journalist Guan Zhehui): Ding Hao, a handicapped student who was orphaned as a child and grew up in the children's welfare home of Hangzhou City, has received notice of acceptance from Hangzhou University to become a student in its philosophy and social sciences department. </seg>
<seg id=3> According to reports, 19-year-old Ding Hao is the first handicapped student raised in an orphanage to attend university since the founding of the People's Republic. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=4> "When I got the notice, I really wanted to jump up," said Ding Hao, though he was not actually able to express his excitement by jumping. </seg>
<seg id=5> A high fever at age of three led to serious bout with polio. That same year he was adopted by the orphanage. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=6> Ding Hao finished his elementary schooling in the orphanage, and then went to a junior high school in a town nearby. </seg>
<seg id=7> At first he was taken to and from school by one of the orphanage's teachers. By his second year he was living at the school, and only went back to the orphanage on Saturdays. Neither wind nor rain could prevent him from attending class. </seg>
<seg id=8> He sat for and passed the university entrance examination this year, and was accepted into Hangzhou University. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=9> Ding Hao's success was due to the combined efforts of every level of society. </seg>
<seg id=10> The orphanage cared and protected for him daily for sixteen years. Since last year they have given him his tuition and have bought materials and food for him, an expense of three thousand Renminbi yuan. </seg>
<seg id=11> Every level of society has embraced him with open arms. </seg>
<seg id=12> Upon learning that Ding Hao had been accepted into university, Hangzhou's Longchang Grain Oil Trade Company donated twenty thousand yuan to assist him at university. A manufacturer of artificial limbs, among other companies, presented him with a wheel chair and a cane. </seg>
</p>
